1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. O-O Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 a6 7. a4 Ba7 8. Na3 ({
More popular is} 8. Re1 {but my choice tries to get the opponent out of book})
8... Qe7 9. Nc2 Be6 10. Bxe6 Qxe6 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Nxe3 $14 {Incredibly, I
could find no games in the database with this position! White should be a tiny
bit better} Ne7 13. Ng5 Qd7 14. Qb3 {Probably not the best square for the
queen, but it looked aggressive} O-O 15. a5 {This advance is not an engine
choice, but a very human move preparing a queenside bind and thus a long range
endgame advantage} h6 16. Nf3 Rab8 17. Rfe1 Ng6 18. Nf5 Qe6 19. Qxe6 $5 {
I could see that the resulting endgame would be double edged with play on
opposite wings. But the nice thing about queenless positions is that I am much
less likely to be mated accidentally!} ({Here} 19. Qc2 {might be slightly
better. I was worried about a possible kingside attack; something the engines
never concern themselves with}) 19... fxe6 20. Ng3 Nf4 21. d4 exd4 22. Nxd4 e5
23. Ndf5 g6 24. Ne3 ({Of course not} 24. Nxh6+ $2 Kh7 {when the knight is
trapped}) 24... Rf7 25. f3 Rbf8 26. Red1 Nd7 27. Nd5 Nc5 28. Nxf4 Rxf4 29. Nf1
Ne6 30. Ne3 Kg7 31. b4 R4f7 32. Nd5 Nf4 33. Rab1 c6 $4 {The game was
progressing logically, but this just drops a crucial pawn and leaves my
opponent hopelessly lost} 34. Nxf4 exf4 35. Rxd6 Rc7 36. Kf2 Re8 37. g3 fxg3+
