1. e4 c5 2. Bc4 {I was glad to see this move, since it avoids all the book
draws. This was the last round and I needed a win for 500 dollars in prize money vs a
draw for only 95 dollars} e6 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. f4 Nge7 $1 {Black's strategy is to play ...
d5 with tempo and avoid White playing e5 with tempo. This move accomplishes
both!} 5. Nf3 d5 6. Bb5 dxe4 $5 {Maybe technically this release of tension is
not the strongest, but it avoids White achieving a pawn wedge later with the
advance e5} 7. Nxe4 a6 8. Bxc6+ Nxc6 9. d3 Be7 10. Be3 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. c3
O-O 13. Qc2 Qd5 {Centralizing the queen on a safe square. White has to worry
about the a2 pawn, but the reaction a3 and b4 is a good plan} 14. a3 Rad8 {
Black's move is a bit oblivious to White's counterplay. The engine likes my
move however} ({In hindsight I would like to play} 14... a5 {here}) 15. Rad1 f5
16. Ng3 e5 $2 {It is necessary to prepare this move with ...g6. Now Black
loses his advantage} 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 18. fxe5 Qxe5 19. Rde1 Qd5 20. d4 $1 {
I had missed that White now attacks the f5 pawn. After defending it, my
opponent gets a protected passed pawn and cuts my position in half} g6 21. c4
Qd6 $6 22. d5 Qd7 ({Another miss. After} 22... f4 {White can just take with}
23. Bxf4 {and my B/e7 hangs!}) 23. Bh6 Rfe8 24. Ne2 $4 ({Absolutely crushing is
} 24. Nh5) ({or} 24. Nxf5) 24... Bd6 $6 ({Black is nearly equal after} 24...
Bh4 25. g3 Bf6 26. Nf4 Bd4+) 25. Nf4 Rxe1 26. Rxe1 Bxf4 27. Bxf4 Re8 28. Be5 $6
{Fortunately my opponent was low on time} ({I thought that opposite colored
bishops after} 28. Rxe8+ Qxe8 29. Qc3 {give Black good drawing chances, but
the weak dark squares around my king promise White long term pressure}) 28...
f4 29. Qd2 Qf5 30. Bc3 Kf7 31. Rxe8 Kxe8 32. Qe2+ Kd7 33. h3 f3 $6 {Taking
advantage of my opponent's time pressure} 34. Qxf3 $4 $11 ({Black's last is
really a bluff, since} 34. gxf3 Qxh3 35. Qe5 {is crushing}) 34... Qxf3 35. gxf3
b5 $1 36. b3 bxc4 37. bxc4 a5 $1 38. Bxa5 Ba6 39. Bb6 Bxc4 40. Bxc5 Bxd5 41.
